<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="un2002g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un2" href="#un2002">UN2: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un2all.htm#un2002g"> (VI.D.7) 2(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> All put to the sword Pardon of Maynooth, Drogheda <small>color t.b.a.</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&hellip; about the middle of March 1535 he <font color="green">[Sir William Skeffington]</font> concentrated his forces about Maynooth, which he carried on the 23rd an important event from a military point of view &hellip; The garrison, including the commandant Parese, who was charged by the Irish, but on insufficient evidence, with having betrayed the place, <mark>were with one or two exceptions put to the sword</mark>. The &lsquo;<mark>Pardon of Maynooth</mark>&rsquo; practically determined the fate of a rebellion which at one time threatened to prove fatal to the English authority in Ireland. <small> <a name="DNBF" href="/udra/udex.htm#DNBF"><cite title="source">Dictionary of National Biography</cite></a> (1889), &ldquo;Thomas Fitzgerald&rdquo;</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Copied to <a name="s12007a" href="s12all.htm#s12007a">Sheet 12.007(a)</a>. From the form of the unit in the notesheets, it seems that Joyce added &lsquo;Drogheda&rsquo;, a reference to a similar though later massacre, the butchery of the people and garrison of Drogheda by Cromwell in 1649.</mm> </dd></dl>
